      "id": 1,
      "text": "Fort Pierce North grew from a 19th‑century military outpost into a thriving citrus hub, with packing houses lining the railroad tracks.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        11,
        17
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.fortpiercehistory.com/"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The 1928 Okeechobee Hurricane struck Fort Pierce North in the eye of disaster, reshaping the community’s future.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.fortpiercehistory.com/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "During World War II, Fort Pierce beaches trained the Navy’s first Underwater Demolition Teams, the precursors to modern Navy frogmen.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3,
        14
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.fortpiercehistory.com/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The Lucie River, named for Saint Lucia’s feast day, marks one of the earliest European attempts to settle the area.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
